    <!-- Translation notes -->
    <h3>Translation notes</h3>
    <p>Python hides all of this behind the runtime. <code>sys.getrefcount()</code> exposes reference counts; <code>gc.collect()</code> triggers the cycle collector. CPython uses reference counting (immediate collection) plus a generational collector for cycles, not stop-and-copy. The SICP model is closer to what the JVM or Go runtime does with copying/compacting collectors. The vector representation of pairs maps directly to struct-of-arrays layouts in systems programming.</p>


